# BikeSafetyBLE

This module receives warning levels from the Android Bike Safety app via Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE).

The module is intentionally independent from the rest of the firmware. It only handles BLE communication and stores the most recent threat level.

It **does not** control vibration motors, LEDs, or any other hardware. Those decisions are left to the main ESP32 program.

---

# Requirements

ESP32 running the Arduino framework.

Install the following library in the Arduino IDE:

Library Manager →

**NimBLE-Arduino**

Author:
h2zero

This library provides the Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) functionality used by this module.

---

# Files

Copy the following files into your Arduino project:

```
BikeSafetyBLE.h
BikeSafetyBLE.cpp
```

No other files are required.

---

# Usage

Create a global object:

```cpp
BikeSafetyBLE ble;
```

In `setup()` initialize BLE:

```cpp
void setup() {

    Serial.begin(115200);

    ble.begin();

}
```

In the main loop call:

```cpp
void loop() {

    ble.update();

}
```

The current threat level can be read at any time:

```cpp
ThreatLevel level = ble.getThreatLevel();
```

or directly:

```cpp
switch (ble.getThreatLevel()) {

    case ThreatLevel::SAFE:
        // no warning
        break;

    case ThreatLevel::APPROACHING:
        // approaching vehicle
        break;

    case ThreatLevel::DANGER:
        // immediate warning
        break;

}
```

The BLE module automatically keeps this value updated.

---

# Bluetooth behaviour

After startup the ESP32 starts advertising itself as

```
BikeSafetyESP
```

The Android application automatically searches for this device.

Once connected, the Android app sends one byte whenever the warning level changes.

If the phone disconnects, the ESP automatically starts advertising again.

If no valid BLE message has been received for several seconds, the module automatically returns to

```
SAFE
```

to prevent stale warning states.

---

# BLE Protocol

Device Name

```
BikeSafetyESP
```

Service UUID

```
12345678-1234-1234-1234-1234567890ab
```

Characteristic UUID

```
87654321-4321-4321-4321-ba0987654321
```

Payload:

| Value | Meaning |
|-------:|---------|
| 0 | SAFE |
| 1 | APPROACHING |
| 2 | DANGER |

Only a single byte is transmitted.

---

# Public API

The module exposes only four functions.

```cpp
ble.begin();
```

Starts BLE advertising.

```cpp
ble.update();
```

Must be called every loop iteration.

```cpp
ble.getThreatLevel();
```

Returns the most recently received threat level.

```cpp
ble.isConnected();
```

Returns whether a phone is currently connected.

---

# Serial Output

The module prints useful debug information over Serial.

Examples:

```
BikeSafetyBLE started
Advertising...
Phone connected
Threat: 1
Threat: 2
Phone disconnected
```

These messages are intended to simplify debugging.

---

# Notes

The BLE module only receives warning levels.

It deliberately contains **no** motor control, LED control or application logic.

This separation keeps the BLE communication reusable and easy to integrate into larger projects.